    {
      "id": "jshell-101-intro",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "# JShell 101 — Variables, Types & Expressions\n\n**JShell is Java's REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop)** — you can run expressions and statements without boilerplate. No `public static void main`, no class wrapper. Just write Java and see results instantly.\n\n**Key idea:** Variables you declare in one cell persist across all cells in the same session. Think of the notebook as one long JShell session where each cell is a block of input.\n\n## What you'll learn\n- Declaring variables with explicit types and with `var`\n- Primitive types: `int`, `double`, `boolean`, `char`\n- Reference types: `String`\n- Arithmetic and string operations\n- Type casting\n- Printing with `System.out.println` and `System.out.printf`\n- Simple `if`/`else` conditionals",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
      "executed": false,
      "executionCount": null,
